{"title_page": "PopCap Games", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = PopCap Games, Inc.\n| logo = PopCap 2012 logo.svg\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2000}}\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list|John Vechey|Brian Fiete|[[Jason Kapalka]]}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people = Matt Nutt ([[general manager]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-05-02-popcap-seattle-getting-downsized |title=PopCap Seattle getting downsized |first=James |last=Brightman |date=May 2, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n| products = [[List of PopCap games|List of games]]\n| num_employees = ~400<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/5720830/ten-years-of-popcap-games |title=Ten Years of PopCap Games |first=Brian |last=Crecente |date=January 1, 2011 |website=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2010\n| parent = [[Electronic Arts]] (2011\u2013present)\n| divisions = {{Unbulleted list|PopCap Vancouver|PopCap Shanghai|PopCap Hyderabad}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.ea.com/studios/popcap/about|ea.com/studios/popcap}}\n}}\n\n'''PopCap Games, Inc.''' is an American [[video game developer]] based in [[Seattle]]. The company was founded in 2000 by John Vechey, Brian Fiete and Jason Kapalka; it was acquired by [[Electronic Arts]] in July 2011. The most popular game it made was Plants vs. Zombies\n\n== History ==\nPopCap Games was founded by John Vechey, Brian Fiete and Jason Kapalka in 2000. They originally incorporated as \"Sexy Action Cool\", a phrase taken from a poster of [[Desperado (film)|Desperado]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=GDC|title=Classic Game Postmortem - Bejeweled|date=2019-01-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1jlw64ddlg|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> Their first title was a strip poker game called \"Foxy Poker\" and was supposed to serve as a revenue stream for their future titles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTheir first game as PopCap was ''[[Bejeweled]]'', a gem-swapping game, which was supported on all major platforms and awarded by Computer Gaming World Hall Of Fame in 2002. The company expanded in 2005 with the acquisition of Sprout Games, a [[Seattle]]-based casual games developer company like PopCap Games, founded by James Gwertzman. Sprout Games is the creator of the game ''[[Feeding Frenzy (video game)|Feeding Frenzy]]''. The Sprout team helped PopCap to make a sequel to the game, ''[[Feeding Frenzy 2: Shipwreck Showdown]]'', with Gwertzman becoming the Director of Business Development at PopCap. In early 2006, PopCap International was opened, based in Dublin, Ireland, working on product localization, mobile games development, marketing, sales and business development.\n\nPopCap began another round of expansion in July 2007 by buying other casual game developers including the creators of an online consumer portal, SpinTop Games. One week prior, the company acquired the Chicago-based development house Retro64, founded by Mike Boeh, which is best known for their retro-arcade action and puzzle titles. After these acquisitions, the PopCap logo was rebranded, dropping the \"Games\" portion. PopCap's premium games list on their website are mixed with other games from other developers/distributors.\n\nOn April 5, 2011, PopCap announced the creation of a new subsidiary, 4th and Battery, started in order to create \"edgier\" games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/04/05/popcap-launches-edgy-4th-and-battery-label/ |title=PopCap launches edgy '4th & Battery' label |first=Alexander |last=Sliwinski |date=April 5, 2011 |website=[[Engadget]]}}</ref> Their first creation was the game ''[[Unpleasant Horse]]''. On July 12, 2011, [[Electronic Arts]] announced it was acquiring PopCap for $650 million with an additional $100 million stock option.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110712007011/en/EA-Acquire-PopCap-Games |title=EA to Acquire PopCap Games |date=July 12, 2011 |website=[[Business Wire]]}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2012, PopCap fired 50 employees in North America in a move to address a shift to mobile and free-to-play games and evaluated ceasing operations of its Dublin studio.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-08-22/electronic-arts-popcap-games-cuts-jobs-may-close-office |title=Electronic Arts' PopCap Games Cuts Jobs, May Close Office |first=Cliff |last=Edwards |date=August 22, 2012 |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]}}</ref> The Dublin studio was closed on September 24, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/ea-closes-popcap-dublin |title=EA closes PopCap Dublin |first=Craig |last=Chapple |date=September 24, 2012 |website=[[MCV/Develop|MCV]]}}</ref>\n\n== Games developed ==\n{{Main|List of PopCap games}}\n\n=== ''Bejeweled'' ===\nPlants vs Zombies\n\nPlants vs Zombies 2: It about time\n\nPlants vs Zombies 3\n\nPlants vs Zombies: Garden warfare\n\nPlants vs Zombies: garden warfare 2{{Main|Bejeweled (series)}}\n\n=== ''Alchemy'' ===\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Alchemy\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = PopCap Games\n| publisher = PopCap Games\n| series = \n| engine = [[PopCap Games Framework]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Mac OS]]\n| released = August 29, 2001\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = Jason Kapalka\n}}\n'''''Alchemy''''' is a [[puzzle video game]] from PopCap Games first introduced on August 29, 2001, and initially available only on the [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,998923,00.html|title=Hooked Again|author=Joshua Quittner|date=January 8, 2001|work=Time}}</ref> In May 2002, a version was made for the [[macOS|Mac]] platform. That June, a version was released that was available for shipping.<ref>http://www.macobserver.com/tmo/article/MacPlay_Ships_Puzzle_Game_Bundle_Bejewled_Alchemy/</ref> That September, a handheld version was released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-26262841_ITM|title=Astraware Launches Five New Games for Pocket PC Handhelds; Premier Developer of PDA Games Converts Popular Palm OS Puzzle and Strategy Games for Use On Pocket PCs}}</ref> This title can be played for free online at various websites minus some components, or a full version can be downloaded and unlocked for a fee. On mobile devices, the game can only be played if downloaded for a fee. The objective of the game is to turn a board of squares from lead to gold by placing randomly generated symbols called ''[[runes]]'' on every square.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TIgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xw4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,4211552&dq=alchemy+game&hl=en</ref>\n\nEach play consists of a rune of a random color and shape being generated by the computer. The rune must be placed directly adjacent to at least one other rune (either above, below, or to the left or right; runes located at a diagonal to the square have no meaning), unless the board is totally blank. All runes that are adjacent to the square where a rune is being placed must share its color or shape.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/449977841.html?dids=449977841:449977841&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+12%2C+2001&author=Joseph+Gelmis&pub=The+Spectator&desc=Games+for+all+types+are+free+on+the+Internet&pqatl=google|title=Games for all types are free on the Internet|last=Gelmis|first=Joseph|date=October 12, 2001}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.ea.com/studios/popcap}}\n\n{{Electronic Arts}}\n{{PopCap}}\n\n[[Category:Electronic Arts]]\n[[Category:PopCap games|*]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:2011 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = PopCap Games, Inc.\n| logo = PopCap 2012 logo.svg\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2000}}\n| founders = {{Unbulleted list|John Vechey|Brian Fiete|[[Jason Kapalka]]}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people = Matt Nutt ([[general manager]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-05-02-popcap-seattle-getting-downsized |title=PopCap Seattle getting downsized |first=James |last=Brightman |date=May 2, 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]]}}</ref>\n| products = [[List of PopCap games|List of games]]\n| num_employees = ~400<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/5720830/ten-years-of-popcap-games |title=Ten Years of PopCap Games |first=Brian |last=Crecente |date=January 1, 2011 |website=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref>\n| num_employees_year = 2010\n| parent = [[Electronic Arts]] (2011\u2013present)\n| divisions = {{Unbulleted list|PopCap Vancouver|PopCap Shanghai|PopCap Hyderabad}}\n| website = {{URL|https://www.ea.com/studios/popcap/about|ea.com/studios/popcap}}\n}}\n\n'''PopCap Games, Inc.''' is an American [[video game developer]] based in [[Seattle]]. The company was founded in 2000 by John Vechey, Brian Fiete and Jason Kapalka; it was acquired by [[Electronic Arts]] in July 2011.\n\n== History ==\nPopCap Games was founded by John Vechey, Brian Fiete and Jason Kapalka in 2000. They originally incorporated as \"Sexy Action Cool\", a phrase taken from a poster of [[Desperado (film)|Desperado]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=GDC|title=Classic Game Postmortem - Bejeweled|date=2019-01-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e1jlw64ddlg|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> Their first title was a strip poker game called \"Foxy Poker\" and was supposed to serve as a revenue stream for their future titles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTheir first game as PopCap was ''[[Bejeweled]]'', a gem-swapping game, which was supported on all major platforms and awarded by Computer Gaming World Hall Of Fame in 2002. The company expanded in 2005 with the acquisition of Sprout Games, a [[Seattle]]-based casual games developer company like PopCap Games, founded by James Gwertzman. Sprout Games is the creator of the game ''[[Feeding Frenzy (video game)|Feeding Frenzy]]''. The Sprout team helped PopCap to make a sequel to the game, ''[[Feeding Frenzy 2: Shipwreck Showdown]]'', with Gwertzman becoming the Director of Business Development at PopCap. In early 2006, PopCap International was opened, based in Dublin, Ireland, working on product localization, mobile games development, marketing, sales and business development.\n\nPopCap began another round of expansion in July 2007 by buying other casual game developers including the creators of an online consumer portal, SpinTop Games. One week prior, the company acquired the Chicago-based development house Retro64, founded by Mike Boeh, which is best known for their retro-arcade action and puzzle titles. After these acquisitions, the PopCap logo was rebranded, dropping the \"Games\" portion. PopCap's premium games list on their website are mixed with other games from other developers/distributors.\n\nOn April 5, 2011, PopCap announced the creation of a new subsidiary, 4th and Battery, started in order to create \"edgier\" games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/04/05/popcap-launches-edgy-4th-and-battery-label/ |title=PopCap launches edgy '4th & Battery' label |first=Alexander |last=Sliwinski |date=April 5, 2011 |website=[[Engadget]]}}</ref> Their first creation was the game ''[[Unpleasant Horse]]''. On July 12, 2011, [[Electronic Arts]] announced it was acquiring PopCap for $650 million with an additional $100 million stock option.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110712007011/en/EA-Acquire-PopCap-Games |title=EA to Acquire PopCap Games |date=July 12, 2011 |website=[[Business Wire]]}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2012, PopCap fired 50 employees in North America in a move to address a shift to mobile and free-to-play games and evaluated ceasing operations of its Dublin studio.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-08-22/electronic-arts-popcap-games-cuts-jobs-may-close-office |title=Electronic Arts' PopCap Games Cuts Jobs, May Close Office |first=Cliff |last=Edwards |date=August 22, 2012 |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]}}</ref> The Dublin studio was closed on September 24, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mcvuk.com/development/ea-closes-popcap-dublin |title=EA closes PopCap Dublin |first=Craig |last=Chapple |date=September 24, 2012 |website=[[MCV/Develop|MCV]]}}</ref>\n\n== Games developed ==\n{{Main|List of PopCap games}}\n\n=== ''Bejeweled'' ===\n{{Main|Bejeweled (series)}}\n\n=== ''Alchemy'' ===\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Alchemy\n| image = \n| caption = \n| developer = PopCap Games\n| publisher = PopCap Games\n| series = \n| engine = [[PopCap Games Framework]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[Mac OS]]\n| released = August 29, 2001\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = Jason Kapalka\n}}\n'''''Alchemy''''' is a [[puzzle video game]] from PopCap Games first introduced on August 29, 2001, and initially available only on the [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] platform.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,998923,00.html|title=Hooked Again|author=Joshua Quittner|date=January 8, 2001|work=Time}}</ref> In May 2002, a version was made for the [[macOS|Mac]] platform. That June, a version was released that was available for shipping.<ref>http://www.macobserver.com/tmo/article/MacPlay_Ships_Puzzle_Game_Bundle_Bejewled_Alchemy/</ref> That September, a handheld version was released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-26262841_ITM|title=Astraware Launches Five New Games for Pocket PC Handhelds; Premier Developer of PDA Games Converts Popular Palm OS Puzzle and Strategy Games for Use On Pocket PCs}}</ref> This title can be played for free online at various websites minus some components, or a full version can be downloaded and unlocked for a fee. On mobile devices, the game can only be played if downloaded for a fee. The objective of the game is to turn a board of squares from lead to gold by placing randomly generated symbols called ''[[runes]]'' on every square.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TIgsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xw4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,4211552&dq=alchemy+game&hl=en</ref>\n\nEach play consists of a rune of a random color and shape being generated by the computer. The rune must be placed directly adjacent to at least one other rune (either above, below, or to the left or right; runes located at a diagonal to the square have no meaning), unless the board is totally blank. All runes that are adjacent to the square where a rune is being placed must share its color or shape.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/449977841.html?dids=449977841:449977841&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+12%2C+2001&author=Joseph+Gelmis&pub=The+Spectator&desc=Games+for+all+types+are+free+on+the+Internet&pqatl=google|title=Games for all types are free on the Internet|last=Gelmis|first=Joseph|date=October 12, 2001}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.ea.com/studios/popcap}}\n\n{{Electronic Arts}}\n{{PopCap}}\n\n[[Category:Electronic Arts]]\n[[Category:PopCap games|*]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:2011 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "DaEDitR", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added more popcap games)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PopCap_Games"}
{"title_page": "James Rube Garrett Jr.", "text_new": "{{for|Irish ornithologist|James Ramsey Garrett}}\n[[File:@warport.jpg|thumb|220px|James R. Garrett]]\n'''James Rube Garrett Jr.'''  (June 5, 1922 \u2013 March 6, 2011)  is the author of ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal, An Eyewitness Account of the Battle of Guadalcanal''. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070211031833/http://www.nettally.com/~jrube/index2.html] He was a Corporal, the Ammo Chief for I Battery, [[3rd Battalion 11th Marines|3rd Battalion]], [[11th Marine Regiment (United States)|11th Regiment]] and a charter member of the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]], formed in Cuba in 1940.\n\nGarrett penned diary entries during his four months of action at the Battle of Guadalcanal.  They detail the war in the Solomons as he lived it...one day at a time.  This is a true eyewitness account of the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]] captured by a young 20-year-old Marine just as it was written many years ago.\n \nHis diary is cited and recognized by historians, universities, libraries, students, and people across the globe aiding in understanding not only the critical strategic and tactical elements of this battle, but the everyday life of a young Marine intent on his duty.\n \n----\n <center> \"Before Guadalcanal the enemy advanced at his pleasure -- after Guadalcanal he retreated at ours.\" - Admiral \"Bull\" [[William Halsey]]\n\n</center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n<center>Excerpt from ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' -</center>\n\nNovember 12, 1942\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Was given word to pack up and move at 3 o'clock. In rear echelon. Saw the most unusual sight yet. 16 torpedo planes shot down by 28 ships that were in the harbor. Big planes being shot down by [[Grumman]]s and [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft fire]]. Really beautiful.\n\nThey flew in low, about 50 feet over the water. I remember we had 30 or 40 or 50 ships sitting in the harbor there, and tall grass covered dunes which you could get on and pretty much have a panoramic view of the whole bay. I remember seeing a big air raid come in and black anti-aircraft fire was coming crazy from all the ships in the harbor -- all kind of puffs of smoke hit the sky. In fact there were 16 torpedo bombers come over and I don't think they hit a thing; they were all being shot down and I think one or two got past the fleet. Our planes were after them too. And way out there on the horizon, we saw the last one go down -- all of them were shot down -- we could see the fire and the smoke. These were big two motor bombers: Japanese bombers burn real good.\"\n</blockquote>\n[[File:@137th.jpg]]\n\n'''<center>13th Platoon Boot Camp [[Quantico Marine Base]] Virginia 1940 ''\"...less than half returned. \"''</center>'''\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|James Rube Garrett Jr.}}\n*[[Battle of Guadalcanal]]\n*[[Guadalcanal]]\n*[[List of World War II battles]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nettally.com/jrube/indx2.html] ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' can be found online and has numerous photographs which are of particular value to anyone interested in Guadalcanal.\n*Beyond All Boundaries  [http://www.nationalww2museum.org/]\n*Beyond All Boundaries: Rube Garrett:  [https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0185078/bio]\n*Garrett's award-winning site featuring his ''Marine Diary'' is listed on the official website of [[Solomon Islands]] Department of Commerce [https://web.archive.org/web/20080516011453/http://www.commerce.gov.sb/Gallery/Guadalcanal.htm].\n*Garrett's ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' is one of the top 100 websites: ''World War II on the Web'' by J. Douglas Smith, Richard Jensen \"...one of the very best sites on Guadalcanal.\"  [https://books.google.com/books?id=iROGEMLAnxMC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=marine+diary+garrett&source=web&ots=zWhqS1ijGI&sig=x-KAwbtzWT0ngLMvYmMASLRqKgA&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=4&ct=result]\n*''A Marine Diary'' Listed by Osprey's Publishing: Military History as a \"favorite.\" [http://www.ospreypublishing.com/content5.php/cid=42]\n*Referenced on: Military.com [http://www.military.com/Content/MoreContent?file=ML_schmid_bkp]  The Official Site of the Medal of Honor [http://www.medalofhonor.com/WorldWarIILinks.htm]\n*''A Marine Diary'' is frequently noted on educational sites as historical evidence to the facts of the battle:\n*[[Encyclopedia of American History]] [http://www.answers.com/topic/guadalcanal-campaign]\n*The History Teacher [http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ht/34.1/tzeng.html]\n*[[eMINTS]]:  Professional development for educators by educators [https://web.archive.org/web/20080607211303/http://www.emints.org/about/index.shtml]\n*ibiblio.org:  the public's library and digital archive [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/PTO/Hell/index.html]\n\nMcGraw-Hill Online Learning Center: A History of the Modern World, 9/e\nR R Palmer, Yale University; Joel Colton, Duke University; Lloyd Kramer, University of North Carolina Chapel Hill [https://web.archive.org/web/20081122150305/http://highered.mcgraw-hill.com/sites/0072316551/student_view0/chapter21/chapter_outline.html]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, James R.}}\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:Guadalcanal Campaign]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|Irish ornithologist|James Ramsey Garrett}}\n[[File:@warport.jpg|thumb|220px|James R. Garrett]]\n'''James Rube Garrett Jr.'''  (June 5, 1922 \u2013 March 6, 2011)  is the author of ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal, An Eyewitness Account of the Battle of Guadalcanal''. [https://web.archive.org/web/20070211031833/http://www.nettally.com/~jrube/index2.html] He was a Corporal, the Ammo Chief for I Battery, [[3rd Battalion 11th Marines|3rd Battalion]], [[11th Marine Regiment (United States)|11th Regiment]] and a charter member of the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]], formed in Cuba in 1940.\n\nGarrett penned diary entries during his four months of action at the Battle of Guadalcanal.  They detail the war in the Solomons as he lived it...one day at a time.  This is a true eyewitness account of the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]] captured by a young 20-year-old Marine just as it was written many years ago.\n \nHis diary is cited and recognized by historians, universities, libraries, students, and people across the globe aiding in understanding not only the critical strategic and tactical elements of this battle, but the everyday life of a young Marine intent on his duty.\n \n----\n <center> \"Before Guadalcanal the enemy advanced at his pleasure -- after Guadalcanal he retreated at ours.\" - Admiral \"Bull\" [[William Halsey]]\n\n</center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n<center>Excerpt from ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' -</center>\n\nNovember 12, 1942\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Was given word to pack up and move at 3 o'clock. In rear echelon. Saw the most unusual sight yet. 16 torpedo planes shot down by 28 ships that were in the harbor. Big planes being shot down by [[Grumman]]s and [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft fire]]. Really beautiful.\n\nThey flew in low, about 50 feet over the water. I remember we had 30 or 40 or 50 ships sitting in the harbor there, and tall grass covered dunes which you could get on and pretty much have a panoramic view of the whole bay. I remember seeing a big air raid come in and black anti-aircraft fire was coming crazy from all the ships in the harbor -- all kind of puffs of smoke hit the sky. In fact there were 16 torpedo bombers come over and I don't think they hit a thing; they were all being shot down and I think one or two got past the fleet. Our planes were after them too. And way out there on the horizon, we saw the last one go down -- all of them were shot down -- we could see the fire and the smoke. These were big two motor bombers: Japanese bombers burn real good.\"\n</blockquote>\n[[File:@137th.jpg]]\n\n'''<center>13th Platoon Boot Camp [[Quantico Marine Base]] Virginia 1940 ''\"...less than half returned. \"''</center>'''\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|James Rube Garrett Jr.}}\n*[[Battle of Guadalcanal]]\n*[[Guadalcanal]]\n*[[List of World War II battles]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nettally.com/jrube/indx2.html] ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' can be found online and has numerous photographs which are of particular value to anyone interested in Guadalcanal.\n*Beyond All Boundaries  [http://www.nationalww2museum.org/]\n*Beyond All Boundaries: Rube Garrett:  [https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0185078/bio]\n*Garrett's award-winning site featuring his ''Marine Diary'' is listed on the official website of [[Solomon Islands]] Department of Commerce [https://web.archive.org/web/20080516011453/http://www.commerce.gov.sb/Gallery/Guadalcanal.htm].\n*Garrett's ''A Marine Diary: My Experiences on Guadalcanal'' is one of the top 100 websites: ''World War II on the Web'' by J. Douglas Smith, Richard Jensen \"...one of the very best sites on Guadalcanal.\"  [https://books.google.com/books?id=iROGEMLAnxMC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=marine+diary+garrett&source=web&ots=zWhqS1ijGI&sig=x-KAwbtzWT0ngLMvYmMASLRqKgA&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=4&ct=result]\n*''A Marine Diary'' Listed by Osprey's Publishing: Military History as a \"favorite.\" [http://www.ospreypublishing.com/content5.php/cid=42]\n*Referenced on: Military.com [http://www.military.com/Content/MoreContent?file=ML_schmid_bkp]  The Official Site of the Medal of Honor [http://www.medalofhonor.com/WorldWarIILinks.htm]\n*''A Marine Diary'' is frequently noted on educational sites as historical evidence to the facts of the battle:\n*[[Encyclopedia of American History]] [http://www.answers.com/topic/guadalcanal-campaign]\n*The History Teacher [http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ht/34.1/tzeng.html]\n*[[eMINTS]]:  Professional development for educators by educators [https://web.archive.org/web/20080607211303/http://www.emints.org/about/index.shtml]\n*ibiblio.org:  the public's library and digital archive [http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/PTO/Hell/index.html]\n\nMcGraw-Hill Online Learning Center: A History of the Modern World, 9/e\nR R Palmer, Yale University; Joel Colton, Duke University; Lloyd Kramer, University of North Carolina Chapel Hill [https://web.archive.org/web/20081122150305/http://highered.mcgraw-hill.com/sites/0072316551/student_view0/chapter21/chapter_outline.html]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garrett, James R.}}\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:Guadalcanal Campaign]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Rube_Garrett_Jr."}
{"title_page": "History of Toru\u0144", "text_new": "The first settlement in the vicinity of [[Toru\u0144]] is dated by [[archaeologists]] to 1100 [[Before Christ|BC]] ([[Lusatian culture]]).<ref>[http://www.dziejba.org/strony/english/summary.htm Hypothetical reconstruction of a Lusatian culture settlement, built using bronze age tools: Wola Radziszowska, Poland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219100632/http://www.dziejba.org/strony/english/summary.htm |date=2012-02-19 }}, part of a study by scientists from the [[Jagiellonian University]]\u2019s Institute Of Archaeology.</ref> During early medieval times, in the 7th through 13th centuries, it was the location of an old Slavonic settlement,<ref name=\"PWN\">Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN Warsaw 1976</ref> at a ford in the Vistula river.\n\nIn spring 1231 the [[Teutonic Knights]] crossed the river [[Vistula]] at the height of Nessau and established a fortress. On 28 December 1233, the Teutonic Knights [[Hermann von Salza]] and [[Hermann Balk]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111019152838/http://torun.pl/portal/index.php?strona=zw_krzy \"Krzy\u017cacy \u2013 za\u0142o\u017cyciele Torunia\" (Teutonic Knights \u2014 the founders of Thorn).] (Internet Archive) Urz\u0105d Miasta Torunia. \"The foundation charter for Thorn was signed on 28th December 1233 by the Grand Master of the Teutonic Order Herman von Salza and the National Master for Prussia and the Slavonic Lands Herman Balka. In that way Thorn was founded by the Teutonic Order and managed by the Knights until 1454.\" Retrieved June 16, 2013.</ref>  signed the foundation charters for Thorn and [[Che\u0142mno]]. The original document was lost in 1244. The set of rights in general is known as [[Kulm law]]. In 1236, due to frequent flooding,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historischcompa00tpgoog/page/n186 <!-- pg=167 quote=28 December 1233 Salza. --> Max T\u00f6ppen ''Historisch-comparative Geographie von Preussen: Nach den Quellen, namentlich auch archivalischen''], J. Perthes, 1858;  [https://archive.org/details/historischcompa00tpgoog PDF]</ref> it was relocated to the present site of the Old Town. In 1239 [[Franciscan]] friars settled in the city, followed in 1263 by [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]]. In 1264 the adjacent New Town was founded predominantly to house Toru\u0144's growing population of craftsmen and artisans. In 1280, the city (or as it was then, both cities) joined the mercantile [[Hanseatic League]], and thus became an important medieval trade centre.\n[[File:Torun Ratusz Staromiejski 01.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Gothic City Hall (''Ratusz'') started in the 13th century]]\n\nThe [[Peace of Thorn (1411)|First Peace of Thorn]] ending the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian\u2013Teutonic War]] was signed in the city in February 1411. In 1440, the gentry of Thorn formed the [[Prussian Confederation]], and in 1454 rose with the Confederation against the [[Monastic state of the Teutonic Knights]], when its delegation submitted a petition to Polish King [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]] asking him to regain power over Prussia as the rightful ruler. An act of incorporation was signed in [[Krak\u00f3w]] (6 March 1454), recognizing the region, including Toru\u0144, as part<ref>F. Kiryk, J. Ry\u015b, Wielka Historia polski, t. II, 1320-1506, Krak\u00f3w 1997, p. 160-161.</ref> of the [[Kingdom of Poland (1385\u20131569)|Polish Kingdom]]. Those events led to the [[Thirteen Years' War (1454\u201366)|Thirteen Years' War]]. After almost 200 years, the New and Old Towns amalgamated in 1454. The Poles destroyed the Teutonic castle. During the war Toru\u0144 financially supported the Polish Army. The Thirteen Years' War ended in 1466 with the [[Second Peace of Thorn (1466)|Second Peace of Thorn]], in which the Teutonic Order ceded their control over western provinces, henceforth [[Royal Prussia]]. Toru\u0144 became part of [[Kingdom of Poland (1385\u20131569)|Kingdom of Poland]].\n\nThe Polish King granted the town great privileges, similar to those of [[Gda\u0144sk]]. In 1501, Polish King [[John I Albert]] died in Toru\u0144 and his heart was buried in Toru\u0144's [[Toru\u0144 Cathedral|St. John's Church]]. In 1506 Toru\u0144 became a [[royal city]] of Poland. In 1528, the royal mint started operating in Toru\u0144. A city of great wealth and influence, it enjoyed voting rights during the [[Royal elections in Poland|royal election]] period.<ref>Polska Encyklopedia Szlachecka, t. I, Warsaw 1935, p. 42.</ref> It was also one of four largest cities of Poland.<ref>Maria Bogucka, ''Miasto i mieszczanin w spo\u0142ecze\u0144stwie Polski nowo\u017cytnej XVI-XVIII w.'', Warsaw 2009</ref> [[Sejm of the Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth|Sejms of the Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth]] were held in Toru\u0144 in 1576 and 1626.<ref>W\u0142adys\u0142aw Konopczy\u0144ski, [http://www.wbc.poznan.pl/dlibra/docmetadata?id=2048&dirids=1 ''Chronologia sejm\u00f3w polskich 1493-1793''].</ref>\n\n[[File:Torun Hartknoch.jpg|thumb|''Thorn'' in [[Christoph Hartknoch]]'s ''Old and New Prussia'' (1684)]]\nIn 1557, during the [[Protestant Reformation]], the city adopted [[Protestantism]], while most Polish cities remained [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]. Under Mayor [[Heinrich Stroband]] (1586\u20131609), the city became centralized. Administrative power passed into the hands of the city council. In 1595 [[Jesuits]] arrived to promote the [[Counter-Reformation]], taking control of St. John's Church. The Protestant city officials tried to limit the influx of Catholics into the city, as Catholics (Jesuits and [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friars) already controlled most of the churches, leaving only St. Mary's to Protestant citizens.\n\nIn 1677 the Prussian historian and educator [[Christoph Hartknoch]] was invited to be director of the [[Gymnasium (school)|Thorn Gymnasium]], a post which he held until his death in 1687. Hartknoch wrote histories of [[Prussia]], including the cities of [[Royal Prussia]].\n\nDuring the [[Great Northern War]] (1700\u201321), the city was besieged by Swedish troops. The restoration of [[Augustus the Strong]] as King of Poland was prepared in the town in the [[Treaty of Thorn (1709)]] by Russian Tsar [[Peter I of Russia|Peter the Great]]. In the second half of the 17th century, tensions between Catholics and Protestants grew, similarly to religious wars throughout Europe in the previous century. In the early 18th century about 50 percent of the populace, especially the gentry and middle class, were German-speaking Protestants, while the other 50 percent were Polish speaking Roman Catholics.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=XsRuj9KMnpIC&pg=PA223&dq=Thorn+Jablonski&hl=de&ei=5wtETbm6NciOswac1ZTHDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Thorn%20Jablonski&f=false\n|title=Daniel Ernst Jablonski; Religion, Wissenschaft und Politik um 1700|first1=Joachim|last1=Bahlcke|page=227|publisher=|year=2008 |language=German|ISBN=978-3-447-05793-6}}</ref> Protestant influence was subsequently pushed back after the [[Tumult of Thorn]] of 1724.\n\n==In the age of the Polish partitions==\nIn 1793 the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] annexed the city following the [[Partitions of Poland|Second Partition of Poland]]. In 1807 [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]] conquered part of the territory and made the city part of the [[Duchy of Warsaw]]. It was ruled by King [[Frederick Augustus I of Saxony|Frederick Augustus I]] of [[Saxony]], but Prussia regained control after Napoleon's defeat in 1814. In 1870 [[French people|French]] [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] taken during the [[Franco-Prussian War]] were directed to build [[Toru\u0144 Fortress|a chain of forts surrounding the town]]. The following year the city, along with the rest of Prussia, became part of the new [[German Empire]]. \n[[File:Most drogowyTORU\u0143.jpg|left|thumb|Toru\u0144 bridge blown up at the beginning of [[Second World War]]]]\n\nToru\u0144 was part of the area subject to Prussian and later German attempts to Germanise the province. Toru\u0144 became a centre of resistance to [[Germanization]] and ''[[Kulturkampf]]'' by Poles, who established a Polish-language newspaper, ''Gazeta Toru\u0144ska''.<ref name=\"PWN\"/> In 1875 a Polish Scientific Society was established, and in 1884 a secret organization dedicated to the restoration of Poland.<ref name=\"PWN\"/> According to the [[Treaty of Versailles]] following [[World War I]] in 1919, Toru\u0144 was part of the [[Polish Corridor]] assigned to [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. It became the capital of the [[Pomeranian Voivodeship (1919\u20131939)|then-Pomeranian Voivodeship]]\nDuring Prussian and German rule, especially in the second half of the 19th century, the German authorities promoted ethnic German settlement in the city by falsifying census results. To diminish the number of Poles, one method involved counting all bilingual Poles who spoke German as Germans. Additionally, German soldiers stationed in the city were included in census figures as citizens for propaganda purposes.<ref name=\"UMT\">\"Toru\u0144 dw\u00f3ch narod\u00f3w.\" ''Gazeta Miejska'' Nr 1 (44) z 13 stycznia 2000, Urzad Miasta Torunia (Toru\u0144 City Council).</ref> In order to achieve German majority over Polish population in Toru\u0144, German authorities helped settle large numbers of German officials, workers and craftsmen by legal and administrative means.<ref name=\"LK\">Lidia Kucht\u00f3wna, ''\"Wielkie dni ma\u0142ej sceny,\" Teatr Narodowy na Pomorzu.'' Zak\u0142ad Narodowy im. Ossoli\u0144skich, 1972, pp. 13 - 204</ref> The number of Germans decreased from 30,509 in 1910 to 2,255 in 1926 and further to 2,057 in 1934.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=KVg_tMs_ZPIC&pg=PA365&dq=Goetheschule+Graudenz&hl=de&ei=j-AlTdz_JsvDswaVy9DMAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBTgo#v=onepage&q=%20Graudenz&f=false|title=Polens Politik gegen\u00fcber seiner deutschen Minderheit 1919\u20131939|first1=Albert S.|last1=Kotowski|page=55|publisher=Forschungsstelle Ostmitteleuropa, [[University of Dortmund]] |year=1998 |language=German|ISBN=3-447-03997-3}}</ref> In 1934 the Polish government abrogated the German-Polish treaty of protection of national minorities which was concluded as part of the Versailles treaties granting Poland the [[Polish corridor]].<ref>[http://www.europa.clio-online.de/quelle/id/artikel-3341 Minderheitenschutzvertrag zwischen den Alliierten und Assoziierten Hauptm\u00e4chten und Polen]</ref>\nIn 1925, the Baltic Institute was established in the city, and worked on documenting Polish heritage and history in Pomerania. In general, the [[Interwar period|interwar period]] was a time of significant urban development in Toru\u0144. Major investments were completed in areas such as transportation (new streets, tramway lines and the Pi\u0142sudski Bridge), residential development (many new houses, particularly in [[Bydgoskie Przedmie\u015bcie]] suburb) and public buildings. Following the bridge's construction, in 1938 the nearby town of [[Podg\u00f3rz, Lublin Voivodeship|Podg\u00f3rz]], on the left bank of the Vistula, was incorporated into Toru\u0144.[[File:Toru\u0144 (DerHexer) 2010-07-17 004.jpg|thumb|Modern-day Toru\u0144, located on the banks of the [[Vistula]]]]\n\nThe Jewish community in Toru\u0144 was very active before World War II. Just before the Nazi German [[invasion of Poland]], Jews supported the Polish government fund-raising for Air Defence (Dz.U.R.P.Nr 26, poz. 176) much more generously than average Torunians. The German army entered the city on September 7, 1939. By the end of November the city was declared ''Judenfrei'', with several hundred Jews who chose to stay, deported to the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto]] and other locations in the ''Warthegau''.<ref name=\"kirkuty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kirkuty.xip.pl/torun_zydzi.htm |title=Zarys historii Torunskiej mniejszosci \u017bydowskiej (History of Jews in Torun) |publisher=Cmentarze \u017bydowskie w Polsce |work=\u017bydzi z Torunia |year=2013 |accessdate=2013-06-16 |author=Maciej Ko\u0142yszko}}</ref> [[Nazi Germany]] annexed the city, and administered it as part of [[Danzig-West Prussia]].  Poles were classified as [[Untermenschen]] by German authorities, with their fate being slave-labor, executions and [[Expulsion of Poles by Nazi Germany|expulsions]]. {{details|Expulsion of Poles by Nazi Germany}}\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the Germans used the chain of forts surrounding the city as [[POW]] camps, known collectively as [[Stalag XX-A]]. The city escaped significant destruction during the war. In 1945 it was taken by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]]. The remaining ethnic German population was [[Expulsion of Germans after World War II|forcibly expelled]], primarily to [[East Germany]], between 1945 and 1947.\n\nAfter World War II, the population increased more than twofold and industry developed significantly. The founding of the [[Nicolaus Copernicus University in Toru\u0144|Nicolaus Copernicus University]] in 1945 was significant. Over the years, it has become one of the best universities in Poland. The university has strongly influenced the intellectual, artistic and cultural life of the city, as well as its perception by non-locals. The university was founded by Polish professors formerly associated with the [[Vilnius University|University of Wilno]]. After the war, they were forced to move to post-1945 Poland.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population \n! Remarks  \n|-\n|1768 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|approx. 1,000 ||\n|- \n|1793 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,570||{{small|(cit: ''Historia Torunia'')}} <ref name=\"Biskup\">Marian Biskup (ed), ''Historia Torunia'' (The History of the City of Toru\u0144), Vol I, II. Instytut Historii ([[Polska Akademia Nauk]]). {{in lang|pl}}</ref>\n|- \n|1806 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,954 ||\n|- \n|1815 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,095 ||\n|-\n|1828 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|11,265 ||\n|-\n|1831 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,631 ||{{small|(cit: ''Preu\u00dfische Landes'' 1835)}} <ref name=\"AEP\" >August Eduard Preu\u00df: ''Preu\u00dfische Landes- und Volkskunde''.  K\u00f6nigsberg 1835, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_L_sAAAAAcAAJ/page/n435 pp. 413\u2013416, no. 30.]</ref> \n|-\n|1864 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|14,106 ||{{small|without German military:}} 2,111 <ref name=\"Steinm\" >Steinmnn: ''Der Kreis Thorn \u2013 Statistische Beschreibung'', Thorn 1866,  [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_DS0BAAAAcAAJ/page/n58 p. 47.]</ref> \n|-\n|1875 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|18,631 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\">Michael Rademacher: ''[http://www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/dan_thorn.html Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Provinz Westpreu\u00dfen, Stadt- und Landkreis Thorn]'' (2006).</ref> \n|-\n|1880 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|20,617 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1885 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|23,906 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1890 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|27,018 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1900 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|29,635  ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1906 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|43,435 ||including German military <ref name=\"MKL\" >''Meyers Gro\u00dfes Konversations-Lexikon'', 6th edition, Vol. 19, Leipzig and Vienna 1907, p. 501\u2013502.</ref>\n|-\n|1910 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|46,227 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|- \n|1931 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|54,280 ||{{small|(cit: ''GUS'')}}\n|-\n|1943 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|78,224||\n|-\n|2009 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|205,934 ||{{small|(cit: ''GUS'')}}\n|}\nSince 1989, when local and regional self-government was gradually reintroduced and the market economy was introduced, Toru\u0144, like other cities in Poland, has undergone deep social and economic transformations. Locals debate whether the changes have been as successful as they had hoped for, but Toru\u0144 has recently reclaimed its strong position as a regional leader, together with [[Bydgoszcz]]. Bydgoszcz\u2013Toru\u0144 rivalry has existed for centuries.<ref>[http://www.pomorska.pl/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091204/REPORTAZ/594123468 Rywalizacja toru\u0144skich \"krzy\u017cak\u00f3w\u201d i bydgoskich \"prusak\u00f3w\u201d trwa pi\u0119\u0107set lat!]</ref><ref>[http://www.westpreussen-berlin.de/Vortragsarchiv/Bildungswerk2004/36145.htm Ein Streifzug durch Brombergs Geschichte]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History of Torun}}\n\n[[Category:History of Toru\u0144| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n", "text_old": "The first settlement in the vicinity of [[Toru\u0144]] is dated by [[archaeologists]] to 1100 [[Before Christ|BC]] ([[Lusatian culture]]).<ref>[http://www.dziejba.org/strony/english/summary.htm Hypothetical reconstruction of a Lusatian culture settlement, built using bronze age tools: Wola Radziszowska, Poland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219100632/http://www.dziejba.org/strony/english/summary.htm |date=2012-02-19 }}, part of a study by scientists from the [[Jagiellonian University]]\u2019s Institute Of Archaeology.</ref> During early medieval times, in the 7th through 13th centuries, it was the location of an old Slavonic settlement,<ref name=\"PWN\">Encyklopedia Powszechna PWN Warsaw 1976</ref> at a ford in the Vistula river.\n\nIn spring 1231 the [[Teutonic Knights]] crossed the river [[Vistula]] at the height of Nessau and established a fortress. On 28 December 1233, the Teutonic Knights [[Hermann von Salza]] and [[Hermann Balk]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111019152838/http://torun.pl/portal/index.php?strona=zw_krzy \"Krzy\u017cacy \u2013 za\u0142o\u017cyciele Torunia\" (Teutonic Knights \u2014 the founders of Thorn).] (Internet Archive) Urz\u0105d Miasta Torunia. \"The foundation charter for Thorn was signed on 28th December 1233 by the Grand Master of the Teutonic Order Herman von Salza and the National Master for Prussia and the Slavonic Lands Herman Balka. In that way Thorn was founded by the Teutonic Order and managed by the Knights until 1454.\" Retrieved June 16, 2013.</ref>  signed the foundation charters for Thorn and [[Che\u0142mno]]. The original document was lost in 1244. The set of rights in general is known as [[Kulm law]]. In 1236, due to frequent flooding,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/historischcompa00tpgoog/page/n186 <!-- pg=167 quote=28 December 1233 Salza. --> Max T\u00f6ppen ''Historisch-comparative Geographie von Preussen: Nach den Quellen, namentlich auch archivalischen''], J. Perthes, 1858;  [https://archive.org/details/historischcompa00tpgoog PDF]</ref> it was relocated to the present site of the Old Town. In 1239 [[Franciscan]] friars settled in the city, followed in 1263 by [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]]. In 1264 the adjacent New Town was founded predominantly to house Torun's growing population of craftsmen and artisans. In 1280, the city (or as it was then, both cities) joined the mercantile [[Hanseatic League]], and thus became an important medieval trade centre.\n[[File:Torun Ratusz Staromiejski 01.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Gothic City Hall (''Ratusz'') started in the 13th century]]\n\nThe [[Peace of Thorn (1411)|First Peace of Thorn]] ending the [[Polish\u2013Lithuanian\u2013Teutonic War]] was signed in the city in February 1411. In 1440, the gentry of Thorn formed the [[Prussian Confederation]], and in 1454 rose with the Confederation against the [[Monastic state of the Teutonic Knights]], when its delegation submitted a petition to Polish King [[Casimir IV Jagiellon]] asking him to regain power over Prussia as the rightful ruler. An act of incorporation was signed in [[Krak\u00f3w]] (6 March 1454), recognizing the region, including Toru\u0144, as part<ref>F. Kiryk, J. Ry\u015b, Wielka Historia polski, t. II, 1320-1506, Krak\u00f3w 1997, p. 160-161.</ref> of the [[Kingdom of Poland (1385\u20131569)|Polish Kingdom]]. Those events led to the [[Thirteen Years' War (1454\u201366)|Thirteen Years' War]]. After almost 200 years, the New and Old Towns amalgamated in 1454. The Poles destroyed the Teutonic castle. During the war Toru\u0144 financially supported the Polish Army. The Thirteen Years' War ended in 1466 with the [[Second Peace of Thorn (1466)|Second Peace of Thorn]], in which the Teutonic Order ceded their control over western provinces, henceforth [[Royal Prussia]]. Toru\u0144 became part of [[Kingdom of Poland (1385\u20131569)|Kingdom of Poland]].\n\nThe Polish King granted the town great privileges, similar to those of [[Gda\u0144sk]]. In 1501, Polish King [[John I Albert]] died in Toru\u0144 and his heart was buried in Toru\u0144's [[Toru\u0144 Cathedral|St. John's Church]]. In 1506 Toru\u0144 became a [[royal city]] of Poland. In 1528, the royal mint started operating in Toru\u0144. A city of great wealth and influence, it enjoyed voting rights during the [[Royal elections in Poland|royal election]] period.<ref>Polska Encyklopedia Szlachecka, t. I, Warsaw 1935, p. 42.</ref> It was also one of four largest cities of Poland.<ref>Maria Bogucka, ''Miasto i mieszczanin w spo\u0142ecze\u0144stwie Polski nowo\u017cytnej XVI-XVIII w.'', Warsaw 2009</ref> [[Sejm of the Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth|Sejms of the Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth]] were held in Toru\u0144 in 1576 and 1626.<ref>W\u0142adys\u0142aw Konopczy\u0144ski, [http://www.wbc.poznan.pl/dlibra/docmetadata?id=2048&dirids=1 ''Chronologia sejm\u00f3w polskich 1493-1793''].</ref>\n\n[[File:Torun Hartknoch.jpg|thumb|''Thorn'' in [[Christoph Hartknoch]]'s ''Old and New Prussia'' (1684)]]\nIn 1557, during the [[Protestant Reformation]], the city adopted [[Protestantism]], while most Polish cities remained [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]. Under Mayor [[Heinrich Stroband]] (1586\u20131609), the city became centralized. Administrative power passed into the hands of the city council. In 1595 [[Jesuits]] arrived to promote the [[Counter-Reformation]], taking control of St. John's Church. The Protestant city officials tried to limit the influx of Catholics into the city, as Catholics (Jesuits and [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friars) already controlled most of the churches, leaving only St. Mary's to Protestant citizens.\n\nIn 1677 the Prussian historian and educator [[Christoph Hartknoch]] was invited to be director of the [[Gymnasium (school)|Thorn Gymnasium]], a post which he held until his death in 1687. Hartknoch wrote histories of [[Prussia]], including the cities of [[Royal Prussia]].\n\nDuring the [[Great Northern War]] (1700\u201321), the city was besieged by Swedish troops. The restoration of [[Augustus the Strong]] as King of Poland was prepared in the town in the [[Treaty of Thorn (1709)]] by Russian Tsar [[Peter I of Russia|Peter the Great]]. In the second half of the 17th century, tensions between Catholics and Protestants grew, similarly to religious wars throughout Europe in the previous century. In the early 18th century about 50 percent of the populace, especially the gentry and middle class, were German-speaking Protestants, while the other 50 percent were Polish speaking Roman Catholics.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=XsRuj9KMnpIC&pg=PA223&dq=Thorn+Jablonski&hl=de&ei=5wtETbm6NciOswac1ZTHDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Thorn%20Jablonski&f=false\n|title=Daniel Ernst Jablonski; Religion, Wissenschaft und Politik um 1700|first1=Joachim|last1=Bahlcke|page=227|publisher=|year=2008 |language=German|ISBN=978-3-447-05793-6}}</ref> Protestant influence was subsequently pushed back after the [[Tumult of Thorn]] of 1724.\n\n==In the age of the Polish partitions==\nIn 1793 the [[Kingdom of Prussia]] annexed the city following the [[Partitions of Poland|Second Partition of Poland]]. In 1807 [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]] conquered part of the territory and made the city part of the [[Duchy of Warsaw]]. It was ruled by King [[Frederick Augustus I of Saxony|Frederick Augustus I]] of [[Saxony]], but Prussia regained control after Napoleon's defeat in 1814. In 1870 [[French people|French]] [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] taken during the [[Franco-Prussian War]] were directed to build [[Toru\u0144 Fortress|a chain of forts surrounding the town]]. The following year the city, along with the rest of Prussia, became part of the new [[German Empire]]. \n[[File:Most drogowyTORU\u0143.jpg|left|thumb|Toru\u0144 bridge blown up at the beginning of [[Second World War]]]]\n\nToru\u0144 was part of the area subject to Prussian and later German attempts to Germanise the province. Toru\u0144 became a centre of resistance to [[Germanization]] and ''[[Kulturkampf]]'' by Poles, who established a Polish-language newspaper, ''Gazeta Toru\u0144ska''.<ref name=\"PWN\"/> In 1875 a Polish Scientific Society was established, and in 1884 a secret organization dedicated to the restoration of Poland.<ref name=\"PWN\"/> According to the [[Treaty of Versailles]] following [[World War I]] in 1919, Toru\u0144 was part of the [[Polish Corridor]] assigned to [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. It became the capital of the [[Pomeranian Voivodeship (1919\u20131939)|then-Pomeranian Voivodeship]]\nDuring Prussian and German rule, especially in the second half of the 19th century, the German authorities promoted ethnic German settlement in the city by falsifying census results. To diminish the number of Poles, one method involved counting all bilingual Poles who spoke German as Germans. Additionally, German soldiers stationed in the city were included in census figures as citizens for propaganda purposes.<ref name=\"UMT\">\"Toru\u0144 dw\u00f3ch narod\u00f3w.\" ''Gazeta Miejska'' Nr 1 (44) z 13 stycznia 2000, Urzad Miasta Torunia (Toru\u0144 City Council).</ref> In order to achieve German majority over Polish population in Toru\u0144, German authorities helped settle large numbers of German officials, workers and craftsmen by legal and administrative means.<ref name=\"LK\">Lidia Kucht\u00f3wna, ''\"Wielkie dni ma\u0142ej sceny,\" Teatr Narodowy na Pomorzu.'' Zak\u0142ad Narodowy im. Ossoli\u0144skich, 1972, pp. 13 - 204</ref> The number of Germans decreased from 30,509 in 1910 to 2,255 in 1926 and further to 2,057 in 1934.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=KVg_tMs_ZPIC&pg=PA365&dq=Goetheschule+Graudenz&hl=de&ei=j-AlTdz_JsvDswaVy9DMAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBTgo#v=onepage&q=%20Graudenz&f=false|title=Polens Politik gegen\u00fcber seiner deutschen Minderheit 1919\u20131939|first1=Albert S.|last1=Kotowski|page=55|publisher=Forschungsstelle Ostmitteleuropa, [[University of Dortmund]] |year=1998 |language=German|ISBN=3-447-03997-3}}</ref> In 1934 the Polish government abrogated the German-Polish treaty of protection of national minorities which was concluded as part of the Versailles treaties granting Poland the [[Polish corridor]].<ref>[http://www.europa.clio-online.de/quelle/id/artikel-3341 Minderheitenschutzvertrag zwischen den Alliierten und Assoziierten Hauptm\u00e4chten und Polen]</ref>\nIn 1925, the Baltic Institute was established in the city, and worked on documenting Polish heritage and history in Pomerania. In general, the [[Interwar period|interwar period]] was a time of significant urban development in Toru\u0144. Major investments were completed in areas such as transportation (new streets, tramway lines and the Pi\u0142sudski Bridge), residential development (many new houses, particularly in [[Bydgoskie Przedmie\u015bcie]] suburb) and public buildings. Following the bridge's construction, in 1938 the nearby town of [[Podg\u00f3rz, Lublin Voivodeship|Podg\u00f3rz]], on the left bank of the Vistula, was incorporated into Toru\u0144.[[File:Toru\u0144 (DerHexer) 2010-07-17 004.jpg|thumb|Modern-day Toru\u0144, located on the banks of the [[Vistula]]]]\n\nThe Jewish community in Toru\u0144 was very active before World War II. Just before the Nazi German [[invasion of Poland]], Jews supported the Polish government fund-raising for Air Defence (Dz.U.R.P.Nr 26, poz. 176) much more generously than average Torunians. The German army entered the city on September 7, 1939. By the end of November the city was declared ''Judenfrei'', with several hundred Jews who chose to stay, deported to the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto]] and other locations in the ''Warthegau''.<ref name=\"kirkuty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kirkuty.xip.pl/torun_zydzi.htm |title=Zarys historii Torunskiej mniejszosci \u017bydowskiej (History of Jews in Torun) |publisher=Cmentarze \u017bydowskie w Polsce |work=\u017bydzi z Torunia |year=2013 |accessdate=2013-06-16 |author=Maciej Ko\u0142yszko}}</ref> [[Nazi Germany]] annexed the city, and administered it as part of [[Danzig-West Prussia]].  Poles were classified as [[Untermenschen]] by German authorities, with their fate being slave-labor, executions and [[Expulsion of Poles by Nazi Germany|expulsions]]. {{details|Expulsion of Poles by Nazi Germany}}\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the Germans used the chain of forts surrounding the city as [[POW]] camps, known collectively as [[Stalag XX-A]]. The city escaped significant destruction during the war. In 1945 it was taken by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]]. The remaining ethnic German population was [[Expulsion of Germans after World War II|forcibly expelled]], primarily to [[East Germany]], between 1945 and 1947.\n\nAfter World War II, the population increased more than twofold and industry developed significantly. The founding of the [[Nicolaus Copernicus University in Toru\u0144|Nicolaus Copernicus University]] in 1945 was significant. Over the years, it has become one of the best universities in Poland. The university has strongly influenced the intellectual, artistic and cultural life of the city, as well as its perception by non-locals. The university was founded by Polish professors formerly associated with the [[Vilnius University|University of Wilno]]. After the war, they were forced to move to post-1945 Poland.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population \n! Remarks  \n|-\n|1768 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|approx. 1,000 ||\n|- \n|1793 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|5,570||{{small|(cit: ''Historia Torunia'')}} <ref name=\"Biskup\">Marian Biskup (ed), ''Historia Torunia'' (The History of the City of Toru\u0144), Vol I, II. Instytut Historii ([[Polska Akademia Nauk]]). {{in lang|pl}}</ref>\n|- \n|1806 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,954 ||\n|- \n|1815 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,095 ||\n|-\n|1828 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|11,265 ||\n|-\n|1831 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,631 ||{{small|(cit: ''Preu\u00dfische Landes'' 1835)}} <ref name=\"AEP\" >August Eduard Preu\u00df: ''Preu\u00dfische Landes- und Volkskunde''.  K\u00f6nigsberg 1835, [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_L_sAAAAAcAAJ/page/n435 pp. 413\u2013416, no. 30.]</ref> \n|-\n|1864 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|14,106 ||{{small|without German military:}} 2,111 <ref name=\"Steinm\" >Steinmnn: ''Der Kreis Thorn \u2013 Statistische Beschreibung'', Thorn 1866,  [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_DS0BAAAAcAAJ/page/n58 p. 47.]</ref> \n|-\n|1875 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|18,631 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\">Michael Rademacher: ''[http://www.verwaltungsgeschichte.de/dan_thorn.html Deutsche Verwaltungsgeschichte Provinz Westpreu\u00dfen, Stadt- und Landkreis Thorn]'' (2006).</ref> \n|-\n|1880 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|20,617 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1885 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|23,906 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1890 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|27,018 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1900 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|29,635  ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|-\n|1906 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|43,435 ||including German military <ref name=\"MKL\" >''Meyers Gro\u00dfes Konversations-Lexikon'', 6th edition, Vol. 19, Leipzig and Vienna 1907, p. 501\u2013502.</ref>\n|-\n|1910 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|46,227 ||{{small|(cit: ''Deutschen Reichs'' 1903\u201315)}} <ref name=\"VWG\"/> \n|- \n|1931 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|54,280 ||{{small|(cit: ''GUS'')}}\n|-\n|1943 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|78,224||\n|-\n|2009 ||style=\"text-align:right;\"|205,934 ||{{small|(cit: ''GUS'')}}\n|}\nSince 1989, when local and regional self-government was gradually reintroduced and the market economy was introduced, Toru\u0144, like other cities in Poland, has undergone deep social and economic transformations. Locals debate whether the changes have been as successful as they had hoped for, but Toru\u0144 has recently reclaimed its strong position as a regional leader, together with [[Bydgoszcz]]. Bydgoszcz\u2013Toru\u0144 rivalry has existed for centuries.<ref>[http://www.pomorska.pl/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20091204/REPORTAZ/594123468 Rywalizacja toru\u0144skich \"krzy\u017cak\u00f3w\u201d i bydgoskich \"prusak\u00f3w\u201d trwa pi\u0119\u0107set lat!]</ref><ref>[http://www.westpreussen-berlin.de/Vortragsarchiv/Bildungswerk2004/36145.htm Ein Streifzug durch Brombergs Geschichte]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History of Torun}}\n\n[[Category:History of Toru\u0144| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n", "name_user": "DayronPL", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Toru%C5%84"}
{"title_page": "10, Janpath", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:Sonia Gandhi welcomes U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Rodham.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Gandhi welcoming U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] to 10, Janpath in 2009.]]\n'''10, Janpath''' is a house on [[Janpath]], [[New Delhi]]. At the time of Rajiv Gandhi's assassination in 1991, while he was campaigning for a second term as Prime Minister of India, 10, Janpath was his official residence, although he lived at 7, Race Course Road while he was Prime Minister. 10, Janpath remains the residence of his widow [[Sonia Gandhi]], who is currently Interim President of [[Indian National Congress]] party (INC).<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sonia-Gandhi-s-power-bill-over-Rs-7-lakh-for-3-years/Article1-623106.aspx Sonia Gandhi's power bill: over Rs 7 lakh for 3 years]. ''Hindustan Times''. 7 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The world according to Sonia|author=Saeed Naqvi|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/37045/ |newspaper=[[Indian Express]] |date=12 December 2003}}</ref> The national headquarters of [[Indian National Congress]] is right behind it on 24, [[Akbar Road]].<ref>[http://www.congress.org.in/new/index.php Indian National Congress] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817015423/http://www.congress.org.in/new/index.php |date=2011-08-17 }} [[Indian National Congress]] website.</ref> It was the residence of India's second Prime Minister, [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]] (1964-1966) and where his body lay in state on 11 January 1966.<ref>{{cite book |title=Days with Lal Bahadur Shastri: Glimpses from The Last Seven Years|author=Rajeshwar Prasad|publisher=Allied Publishers|year=1991|isbn=81-7023-331-3 |page=16 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvTYfnfsec0C&pg=PA16 |ref= }}</ref> Today his biographical museum, ''Lal Bhadur Shastri Memorial'' is at  1, Motilal Nehru Place (formerly 10, Janpath), adjacent to the complex.<ref>{{cite news |title=Can the Congress be saved by its new leaders?|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/jan/10jana.htm |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lest we FORGET... |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2004/10/02/stories/2004100200850200.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe house was the residence of Prime Minister [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]] who succeeded [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] in the 1960s. Adjacent to the complex, facing the roundabout is ''Lal Bahadur Shastri Memorial'' at  1, Motilal Nehru Place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shastri memorial losing out to Sonia security|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/shastri-memorial-losing-out-to-sonia-security/738420/0 |newspaper=Indian Express |date=17 January 2011  }}</ref>\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://wikimapia.org/16918034/10-Janpath 10 Janpath] [[wikimapia]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121018020649/http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?225871 10, Janpath Doors Are Shut]\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n\n{{coord missing|Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Government buildings in Delhi]]\n\n{{india-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n[[File:Sonia Gandhi welcomes U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Rodham.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Gandhi welcoming U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] to 10, Janpath in 2009.]]\n'''10, Janpath''' is a house on [[Janpath]], [[New Delhi]]. At the time of Rajiv Gandhi\u2019s assassination in 1991, while he was campaigning for a second term as Prime Minister of India, 10, Janpath was his official residence, although he lived at 7, Race Course Road while he was Prime Minister. 10, Janpath remains the residence of his widow [[Sonia Gandhi]], who is currently Interim President of [[Indian National Congress]] party (INC).<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Sonia-Gandhi-s-power-bill-over-Rs-7-lakh-for-3-years/Article1-623106.aspx Sonia Gandhi's power bill: over Rs 7 lakh for 3 years]. ''Hindustan Times''. 7 November 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The world according to Sonia|author=Saeed Naqvi|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/37045/ |newspaper=[[Indian Express]] |date=12 December 2003}}</ref> The national headquarters of [[Indian National Congress]] is right behind it on 24, [[Akbar Road]].<ref>[http://www.congress.org.in/new/index.php Indian National Congress] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817015423/http://www.congress.org.in/new/index.php |date=2011-08-17 }} [[Indian National Congress]] website.</ref> It was the residence of India's second Prime Minister, [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]] (1964-1966) and where his body lay in state on 11 January 1966.<ref>{{cite book |title=Days with Lal Bahadur Shastri: Glimpses from The Last Seven Years|author=Rajeshwar Prasad|publisher=Allied Publishers|year=1991|isbn=81-7023-331-3 |page=16 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvTYfnfsec0C&pg=PA16 |ref= }}</ref> Today his biographical museum, ''Lal Bhadur Shastri Memorial'' is at  1, Motilal Nehru Place (formerly 10, Janpath), adjacent to the complex.<ref>{{cite news |title=Can the Congress be saved by its new leaders?|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/jan/10jana.htm |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |date=January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lest we FORGET... |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2004/10/02/stories/2004100200850200.htm |publisher=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 October 2004 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe house was the residence of Prime Minister [[Lal Bahadur Shastri]] who succeeded [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] in the 1960s. Adjacent to the complex, facing the roundabout is ''Lal Bahadur Shastri Memorial'' at  1, Motilal Nehru Place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shastri memorial losing out to Sonia security|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/shastri-memorial-losing-out-to-sonia-security/738420/0 |newspaper=Indian Express |date=17 January 2011  }}</re